    <item>
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cis580/16-models/01-introduction/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 24 Mar 2020 10:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cis580/16-models/01-introduction/index.html</guid>
      <description>With some experience building our own triangle meshes, let&amp;rsquo;s turn our attention to those that have been built for us by artists working with modeling software. These meshes are typically organized into a model - a collection of triangle meshes and transformations that collectively define a complex 3D shape.
Like our earlier examples, we&amp;rsquo;ll start from a starter project with our assets pre-loaded. In addition, we&amp;rsquo;ll include the ICamera interface and the CirclingCamera we created in the lesson on Lights and Cameras , and the Terrain class and IHeightMap interface from our exploration of Heightmap Terrain .</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Model Basics</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cis580/16-models/02-model-basics/index.html</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 24 Mar 2020 10:00:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cis580/16-models/02-model-basics/index.html</guid>
      <description>A model is a collection of the information that defines a 3D object. Rather than being hand-created or hard-coded (as we have done in our previous work), a model is usually created using 3D modeling software (i.e. Blender, 3D Studio, Maya, etc). Instead of exposing the raw data of the meshes, these software packages provide an abstraction, often based on real-world sculpting techniques or constructive geometry transformations that assist artists in creating complex three-dimensional shapes.</description>
    </item>
